to avoid the root user of the host to be the root user of the contaner which is running on the host, we can specify the user in dockerfile while building an image
or to grant different permission to the root user of the container by editing the file here: /usr/include/linux/capability.h
by default, run 'docker run ubuntu' to check what are the default permissions on the container, if you want to update it, run 
'docker run --cap-add MAC_ADMIN ubuntu' sth like that.


1. What is the user to execute the sleep process within the ubuntu-sleeper pod
A:
k exec ubuntu-sleeper -- whoami

2. Edit the pod ubuntu-sleeper running in the default namespace, to run the sleep process with user ID 1010.
A:
step 1, kubectl get pod ubuntu-sleeper -o yaml > ubuntu-sleeper.yaml
step 2, update the ubuntu-sleeper.yaml to run as user 1010 as follows (Note that Kubernetes has an empty default securityContext 
that is automatically added to pod definitions, so make sure to remove or update this one):
securityContext: 
    runAsUser: 1010
step 3, kubectl delete po ubuntu-sleeper --force
kubectl apply -f ubuntu-sleeper.yaml

3. Update the pod ubuntu-sleeper to run as Root user and with the SYS_TIME capability.
A:
in the edit pod step, just replace the previously set runAsUser: 1010 with 
securityContext:        # Updated securityContext on container level
      capabilities:
        add: ["SYS_TIME"]
